    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-22T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-22T16:00:00-05:00" n="194"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d194">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 103.96/1245</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SWG1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-22T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 22, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5976. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 394. Your 476, Embassy’s 5306, October 4, 12 noon,<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d194fn1">Not printed.</note> and your 443, Embassy 5175, September
                    23, 11 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d194fn2">Not printed.</note> We approve in
                    substance of the plan of September 7 accompanying your letter of September 11
                    for black list for Switzerland, as modified to meet objections of French.<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d194fn3">Not printed.</note> We do not, however, favor the
                    presentation of a joint note to the Swiss on this subject, believing that
                    representations with respect to the black list should be kept informal. The
                    substance of the note should therefore, in so far as United States is concerned,
                    be orally presented. Of course, it is to be kept clear, as matter of record,
                    that the War Trade Board bases its black list upon the recommendations of its
                    own representative and is not bound by the decision of the Paris or Berne
                    committees.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
